text: I love it when movies like this come out for three reasons. 1. It allows not only black people but the world to see what historically happened to slaves and to be able to relate that to what is happening now in the present. 2. Although it is still apart of a narrative we are use to, it shows that narrative from the perspective of someone with a different idea of what should be done about the atrocities committed. 3. This movie and what it means and what it symbolizes and what it holds true of our society is that racism, from the era this movie portrays to know, is not only alive but continuously thrives off the belief that this is just the way things are. And that ladies and gentlemen is why stories like these have to be told. All those years ago Nat Turner rose up and fought back against his oppressors and was killed in the process. So this is a PSA to all the racists of America we are a reflection of our ancestors but more evolved to the times. We are Nat Turner , Harriet Tubman, MLK, Malcolm X and so many more. You can not oppress us anymore.

text: "Set against the antebellum South" If you're having reservations about watching this film, know that you can still be a proud present-day American and simultaneously acknowledge the blatant hypocrisy of core Democratic values (freedom, liberty, justice, equality, etc) around that time. And like the human topics of love, hate, envy, jealousy...there is no time constraints nor a statute of limitation on stories, especially those stories that have yet to be told properly, understood in historical context, and compartmentalized for today's youth and blind adults.   If you refuse to acknowledge that this film, despite its black liberation storyline, is part of the overall human condition, you're being complicit in the dehumanization of the slaves and their real stories. Do not succumb to historical amnesia  Remove yourselves from the idea of "here's another slave movie" or "there goes the blacks playing victimhood" narrative because it's disingenuous, serves no purpose in cinema or schools of thought, and actually makes you look a sheep unwilling to navigate the complexities of our social condition. Damn it, it's Nat Turner.   By the way,  "Fox Searchlight Pictures bought worldwide rights to the film in a $17.5 million deal, the largest deal at the film festival to date." Oh yeah, it's a big deal.

text: Nat Turner was a murderer who led other murderers. His group even murdered handfuls of young children. In total, using knives, axes, hatchets, sabers, and various blunt objects they brutally and mercilessly slaughtered around 50 to 65 people in about 36 hours. As a result of his 1831 killing spree, not only did Turner hand slavers the dubious excuse to kill innocent blacks that weren't even involved in his murders,  but Turner also did more to tighten the chains of bondage than any man in American history including marking the beginning of the end for the Southern anti-slave movement. This movie will most likely not present truth or real history, but propaganda and false vindication for those that are obsessed with the hue of their skin and use their color to both horde over others and to gain unmerited advancement at the expense of their fellow citizens.  This is the second motion picture titled "The Birth of a Nation." Ironically, this new film will be as much a political tool of the Liberal Progressive Left as its 1915 counterpart was for the white supremacy movement. Turner was executed November 11th of 1831 after being in hiding for around two months. No man was more justly hanged.

text: Birth of a Nation is NOT a Hollywood production. It is an independent film made outside the Hollywood system by the lead actor and director Nate Parker. He's an unknown actor (formerly a computer programmer) with a few independent films under his belt. The film's budget consisted of 11 different investors who only provided 60%. Then a producer from an independent film company (Bron Studios) in Canada provided the remainder. The film's involvement in "Hollywood" didn't exist until Fox Searchlight Pictures bought the rights to the film back in January of this year where it premiered at Sundance.

text: This looks like an incredibly, well-directed film that hits hard emotionally, but there are definitely concerns about the timing and message this film is sending.  Last year I took a history course at university, and we were discussing the story of Nat Turner.  We read excerpts about the events that unfolded as he plotted revenge against the slaveowners for the injustices of slavery.  But there was a discussion that still gets to me every day:  My teacher celebrated the death of every white person killed by Nat Turner and his followers.  This went beyond slaveowners, but to children as well.  While I understand the terrible treatment slaves went through as they were torn from their homes and brought to America, I don't believe the children of slaveowners "deserved" to die.  It's not as though they chose to be slaveowners, but were rather born into it, being taught to accept and believe the immoral teachings of their parents (most likely just the father considering the time).  When I voiced my point of view to my teacher, I was quickly dismissed and labeled as ignorant by the rest of my peers.  The way I saw it, the children were victims of their own family's wrongdoings.  The way my class saw it (or most of them, at least), was that if they were white and associated with these slaveowners, the children deserved to be killed.    Long story short, I believe people need to think critically about who or what is to blame, and what is actually "right or wrong," if there even is a clear answer.  No one ever tries to understand situations from multiple points of view.  Social media is quick to make us decide what is right and wrong, who is good and who is evil.    Just look at the election.  Obviously, liberals hate Trump.  He's the worst possible figure in their eyes.  Social media is quick to label Trump and his supporters as ignorant, uneducated racists.    Do I agree with their arguments?  No.  Do I understand them, at least to a certain extent?  Yes, at least more than most of my liberal peers.  Trump supporters are frustrated.  They're frustrated w/ how politically correct our nation is becoming.  For one, they don't see a movement like "Black Lives Matter" as being one for equality, but one for a complete shift in power.  Many will disagree with me, but I absolutely see this point with the way Social Media portrays it.  Another example includes immigration.  They are frustrated with the topic of illegal immigration turning into the topic of "immigrants are people too."  -Yes, immigrants are people, my grandparents included.  But they came here legally.  It's not an argument of whether or not you're human beings.  Of course you are!  The argument is about uncontrolled and illegal immigration into the U.S.!  The approaches that liberal movements have been taking are just trying to guilt everyone into taking their side.  They are literally "silencing" the opposition.  In Black Lives Matter, there was literally a trend going around saying "if you stay silent, you are part of the problem."   I realize I'm digressing, but as you can obviously tell, I am frustrated.  I'm a liberal who believes in the foundation of being a liberal, but disagrees with the strategies and courses of action we've taken.  And with that, I'm going to stop my 3am rant and go to bed before I write an essay.  Just be human and think logically guys.  Understand before choosing a side.  One of the most ironic terms is the term "liberal."  It had great intentions, but now people who join automatically believe they are open-minded.  The process starts the other way around.

text: While this looks like a good movie with a fantastic message, it looks like a blatant attempt to rewrite the history of D.W. Griffith's Birth Of A Nation; a highly racist movie in 1915 which glorifies the Klan. Despite the glorified racism in the original it is understood by film scholars to be one of the most influential and pivotal points in the art of filmmaking. Simply put, filming techniques were used that would be carried on for more than 100 years. 2016 birth of a nation appears to be a misleading cover song of the 1915 original. I believe art should be preserved, no matter how ugly or evil the message is. This seems to water down the implications of D.W. Griffith's original film

text: It will be interesting, to say the least, to see how Hollywood frames the story of Nat Turner; to see how they will frame the rebellion in which half of the slaughtered victims were children and infants. If Hollywood's past films are any prediction of the nature of future films, then this will turn out to be a lopsided presentation ‚Äî beyond the most obvious reason. There is nothing wrong with portraying the horrors of the American institution of slavery. On many plantations, blacks were treated worse than livestock. They were starved, beaten, raped, and abused in numerous ways. All of that deserves to be remembered. The problem, however, with relying on Hollywood to be the keeper of America's conscience is that most if not all of its black historical films are intended to serve as finger-wagging for today's headlines (e.g., incidents involving the police, the Black Lives Matter movement, etc.). In other words, we are being told that the systemic problems of 1831 are alive and well in the 21st century.  This is problematic because it glosses over thousands of significant details in the intervening years, from Reconstruction to affirmative action. Within that time-skip, black Americans jostled not only with whites but with themselves, struggling to select leaders whom they believed would best protect their interests. Too often we hear about Malcolm X and absolutely nothing about Booker T. Washington; too much about the brutal actions of Nat Turner and too little about the pulsating, sober intellect of Frederick Douglass.   Not all black Americans thought (or think) alike; yet that is not the image with which we are presented by Hollywood. In neglecting black historical figures whose philosophical ideas differ from today's mainstream progressive-liberalism, Hollywood reveals itself to be no less manipulative than many of the white plantation masters who took it upon themselves to determine what it meant to be black in America. If we had more Hollywood films about Booker T. Washington ‚Äî replete with national advertising ‚Äî we might, at the very least, be compelled to divide our attention between the historical abuses inflicted on black children in the 1830s by white masters and the daily slaughter of black children by black gangsters in today's most "progressive" and "liberal" cities; and in so doing, we might then be compelled to ask ourselves where and with whom the responsibility for that tragedy truly lies.

But ye denied the Holy One and the Just, and desired a murderer to be granted unto you; And KILLED THE PRINCE OF LIFE, WHOM GOD HATH RAISED FROM THE DEAD; whereof we are witnesses. John 8:24 I said therefore unto you, that ye shall die in your sins: for if ye believe not that I am he, ye shall die in your sins.   If you believe this you will have eternal life.   John 3:36 He that believeth on the Son hath EVERLASTING LIFE: and he that believeth not the Son shall not see life; but the wrath of God abideth on him. Ephesians 4:30 And grieve not the holy Spirit of God, whereby YE ARE SEALED unto the day of redemption.   1 Peter 1:5 4-5 To an inheritance incorruptible, and undefiled, and that fadeth not away, reserved in heaven for you,  Who are KEPT by the power of God through faith unto salvation ready to be revealed in the last time.   It is the SHED BLOOD of the LORD Jesus Christ that cleans us.   Hebrews 9:22  And almost all things are by the law purged with blood; and without shedding of blood is no remission.    Colossians 1:20  And, having made peace through the blood of his cross, by him to reconcile all things unto himself; by him, I say, whether they be things in earth, or things in heaven.   Surely this comes at a heavy cost to us? Must we do works of kindness to qualify or earn this salvation? It is 100 percent free!    Ephesians 2:8-9 For by grace are ye saved through faith; and that not of yourselves: it is the GIFT OF GOD: NOT OF WORKS, lest any man should boast.  Ephesians 3:7 Whereof I was made a minister, according to the GIFT OF GRACE of God given unto me by the effectual working of his power.   IF YOU BELIEVE THIS, All you need to do is call on the LORD! text: I was reading a lot of comments and I also noticed all the dislikes for the movie trailer (I don't know the reasons why as everyone has their own person bias)...  Yes, it might be a mixed of facts and fiction in order to dramatize the movie, after all, movie studios still have to make money. But if it gets people interested in history and to research what happened and read and talk and even open up dialogues between different groups (without the insults) of why people feel the way they do or even how history came to be written by our forefathers (the events that transpired), I think this movie shouldn't be negatively shot down (nor praised as I have not seen it yet). History is rarely ever clean, simple or easy to read about. It's just what it is, it can be more times hard, brutal and bloody and it has always been this way and even though it's hard to think things like this could have happened and it will make people cringe in horror at the fact of how history can be brutal and even barbaric and savage, history can still be a powerful tool for positive change and progress, as long as we don't forget where we came from and we don't try to sweep it under the carpet so that people feelings aren't hurt nor rewrite history books to appease anyone for fear of insulting anyone's fragile emotion (defense mechanism most use: forget the past, live in the present) . We should never be afraid, or shy way from facing the truth that through time different groups of people have suffered pain (And yes there were good and bad people, just like there were good and bad white, black, Asians, and so many other people). History also has a lot of great stories of human accomplishments and stories of perseverance, sacrifices, and challenges that had to be faced before success and freedom could be attained by groups all over the world. And if you don't want to see the movie, then pick up a history book, a biography, talk with historians, professors, and research facts on your own and educate yourself about what truly happened and even watch documentaries. There has to be a bridge to connect the new generation so that they can become independent thinkers and remember the many pebbles that it took to build the road they walk on today... And even though it's not a smooth road and there are many bumps, it's the road that they can still improve on by learning and educating themselves on the truth that exists and every journey starts by asking questions that will lead them to a new and sometimes scary adventure through time. Don't let the fear stop you from finding out the truth and accepting that what we take for granted today was hard earned and fought for by the many people who sacrificed and died themselves. So, let's add a smoother stone on the road for future generations to walk on, by leaving today a better place to live in.

text: I no longer understand people. The world is able to collectively agree that the events that took place during WWII were horrific. We can collectively say that the Jewish, Chinese, Native American (and a few other groups) historical experiences in Europe and this part of the world were terrible... But we can't collectively come together and agree that transporting millions of Africans across the Atlantic for the purpose of chattel slavery was bad? We cannot say that one of the worst injustices to happen in this part of the world happened to Africans? The African experience in the Americas should be told and respected in the same manner the Jewish experience (for example) is respected and told. To say that 400 years of history and narratives in the Americas should be "let go" is to basically say that Afro Americans, Canadians, Caribbean and South Americans should let go of a history that has defined their current cultures and existence. Who we are as a people (linguistically, culturally, geographically and so on) is the result of some slaves ability to survive when living or dying meant coin in hand. This is not about hatred (the same way Civil War movies are not about the South being bitter about their loss) this is about a telling of a period in history that should never be forgotten.

There are black people alive today that still remember their parents/grandparents being racially abused, physically assaulted, & even murdered/executed, just for being black (these things are STILL happening to a lesser degree today).  Stop spreading lies about blacks selling blacks to Europeans. If this lie was true, please tell me; what magical currency did Europeans use to pay The Africans with, for their own people?? What use would that currency be to a so-called "primitive" tribes-person?  Africa is the most mineral/resource rich landmass on Earth; what resource could Europeans bribe them with in the 1600s, that Black People didn't already possess??  The truth is, Europeans lied & kidnapped these people by force (hence the need for muskets/guns, nets & iron shackles). These people were not taken willingly, hence the weapons, violence & the term 'kidnap'.  Even if you sold me a dog in prime health, & I beat it, tortured it, worked it to death & then set it on fire. These people are hurting for a reason that many Europeans want to ignore or forget, even though many of these people still feel the effects of this treatment today.......
